The bust of Dalida is an artistic homage to the famous singer and icon of French music, located in the heart of Montmartre, Paris. This memorial captures the essence and lasting influence of Dalida through a sculpture representing her face and vibrant personality. Situated near the house where the singer lived, the bust has become a place of pilgrimage for her fans, who leave flowers, photos, and messages in tribute to her memory. Embodying the spirit of Montmartre and Dalida's cultural legacy, this bust is an important testament to her impact on the French and international music scene.

On a Sunday morning, I took the metro to Lamarck - Caulaincourt . Once, I reached the bronze bust of Dalida, a singer, I continued to walk on Rue de L'Abreuvoir to photograph the scenery. Later, I turned left on Rue des Saules to view the vineyard, named Clos Montmartre. I continued on Rue des Saules to turn right on Rue Saint Vincent to photograph the steep stairs on Rue du Mont-Cenis. I continued my walk on Rue Saint -Vincent then left on Rue de la Bonne, then right on Rue du Chevalier de la Barre to see the Basilica, Sacre-Coeur. Left on Rue du Mont Cenis, then right on Rue Norvins. I turned left onto Place du Tertre to enjoy breakfast at Au Clairon des Chasseurs, while a charming Frenchman sketched a caricature image of me. See the photos, the steep walk is worth it ...I chose to arrive early to avoid the crowds and the early sunlight enhances the beauty of the cobblestone streets. Veronica Vhuntermassage LLC

I have visited the grave of Dalida in Montmartre Cemetery in Paris, so I decided to see Place Dalida, where the bust of this famous singer is located.  I had never heard of Dalida until a woman friend who owns a large oceanfront villa in Tangier, Morocco, but who lives mainly in Montmartre, told me she had bought Dalida‚Äôs house at 11 bis Rue d‚ÄôOrchampt after Dalida committed suicide there in 1987.  On a number of stays in Paris, I have visited my friend in her house, where Dalida once lived for 20 years. It is an imposing five-floor house surrounded by a high stone wall with a garden, and there is another entrance on Rue Lepic. From the first floor salon and upper floors windows there are unobstructed views of Les Invalides and the Tour Eiffel.
